  "prompt": "What is macros?",
  "response": "Macros are a programming concept that allows you to define a set of instructions or code that can be expanded or replaced at compile-time. Here are key points about macros:\n\n1. Definition:\n- A macro is a fragment of code with a name\n- It can take arguments and generate code dynamically\n- Processed by preprocessor before actual compilation\n\n2. Common Uses:\n- Code generation\n- Creating reusable code snippets\n- Defining constants\n- Conditional compilation\n- Performing complex text substitutions\n\n3. Examples in Different Languages:\n\nC/C++:\n```c\n#define MAX(a, b) ((a) > (b) ? (a) : (b))\n```\n\nPython (using decorators):\n```python\ndef macro(func):\n    return func()\n```\n\nRust:\n```rust\nmacro_rules! say_hello {\n    () => {\n        println!(\"Hello!\");\n    };\n}\n```\n\n4. Benefits:\n- Code reusability\n- Performance optimization\n- Improved code readability\n- Flexibility in code generation\n\n5. Potential Drawbacks:\n- Can make code harder to debug\n- May increase compilation time\n- Can lead to unexpected behavior if not used carefully\n\nMacros are powerful tools for meta-programming and code generation.",
